      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 used under ISO 9001-certified QMS; vendor V&V documentation on file; version-controlled simulation scripts archived in institutional repository.",
      "rationale": "The FEA platform (Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2) is deployed under a documented quality management system. Simulation scripts are version-controlled and archived. Vendor-supplied code verification documentation satisfies Gradation 2 requirements for this medium-risk COU."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/numerical-code-verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Vendor benchmark suite results reviewed; at least two canonical structural benchmarks (patch test, cantilever beam) reproduced within 1% of analytical solution.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical passes the NAFEMS benchmark suite. Internal patch-test and cantilever-beam benchmarks reproduced to within 0.3% of closed-form solutions, confirming correct implementation of the linear-elastic and contact formulations used in the pedicle screw model."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/discretization-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study performed on QoIs; GCI < 2% for all three QoIs on the production mesh.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted (coarse 0.8 mm, medium 0.5 mm, fine 0.3 mm global element size at screw-rod interface). Richardson extrapolation yielded GCI values of 1.1%, 1.4%, and 1.7% for stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm respectively. Production mesh is the medium (0.5 mm) configuration."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/numerical-solver-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver residuals < 1e-6 for all load steps; no divergence events in production runs.",
      "rationale": "The sparse direct solver (SPARSE) was used for the linear portion; the nonlinear Newton-Raphson loop converged in ≤ 6 iterations per load step with force residual norm < 1×10⁻⁶. No solver warnings or divergence events were recorded across all 11 specimen-matched simulations."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/use-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent review of model setup by a second analyst; simulation execution checklist completed and archived.",
      "rationale": "A second-analyst independent review of boundary condition assignments, material property inputs, and contact pair definitions was completed prior to production runs. A 27-item simulation execution checklist was signed off and archived in the study record."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/model-form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Continuum FEA with nonlinear contact and elastoplastic titanium material law; model form justified by literature precedent for ASTM F1717 screw constructs.",
      "rationale": "The model employs a continuum finite element representation with Hertz-consistent frictional contact (μ = 0.15) at the screw-rod and screw-vertebral body block interfaces. An isotropic hardening elastoplastic material model (Ti-6Al-4V, bilinear) is used for the screw shaft. This model form is consistent with published FDA guidance and peer-reviewed F1717 simulation studies."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/model-inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from ASTM-certified coupon testing of production-lot Ti-6Al-4V; geometric inputs derived from CMM measurements of test articles; uncertainty in inputs quantified.",
      "rationale": "Elastic modulus (114 GPa), yield strength (880 MPa), and tangent modulus (1.2 GPa) were determined from tensile coupon testing of the same production lot used for bench specimens. Screw geometry was verified against CMM measurements (±0.01 mm). Parametric sensitivity analysis confirmed that ±5% variation in material properties produces < 2% change in QoIs."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/test-samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N ≥ 10 specimens from production lot; tested across two independent laboratories; coefficient of variation < 15% for all QoIs.",
      "rationale": "Eleven constructs assembled from production-lot non-cannulated 7.5 mm screws were distributed across two independent test laboratories (6 at Lab A, 5 at Lab B). Inter-laboratory coefficient of variation was 4.8% for stiffness, 6.2% for yield force, and 5.9% for force at 40 mm, all well below the 15% threshold."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/test-conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of clinical loading scenarios represented in the COU; at minimum two load levels or configurations tested.",
      "rationale": "Testing was performed under a single load configuration (ASTM F1717 standard compression-bending fixture, 5 mm/min crosshead speed, ambient temperature). Only one test condition was evaluated; the required level of 3 demands at least two configurations spanning the COU loading envelope. This factor is below the required level and is documented as a gap. Compensating evidence from the model form and output comparison factors partially offsets this deficiency."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/equivalency-of-input-parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation inputs (geometry, material, boundary conditions) demonstrably equivalent to test article parameters; traceability documented.",
      "rationale": "Each of the 11 simulation instances was parameterized using specimen-specific CMM geometry and coupon-derived material properties from the same production lot. Boundary conditions replicate the ASTM F1717 fixture geometry (35 mm offset, fixed inferior block, actuator displacement applied to superior block). Full traceability from test article serial number to simulation input file is documented in the study record."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/output-comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (E/uval) computed for all three QoIs; E/uval < 1.96 for each; percent difference < 10%.",
      "rationale": "The validation metric E/uval was computed following the FDA-recommended approach (Eq. 4 of the referenced methodology paper). Results: stiffness E/uval = 0.87 (4.2% difference), yield force E/uval = 1.14 (6.1% difference), force at 40 mm E/uval = 1.61 (7.8% difference). All three QoIs satisfy both acceptance criteria."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/relevance-of-qoi",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) are directly linked to clinical performance endpoints and regulatory submission requirements.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness and yield force are the primary mechanical performance endpoints for pedicle screw systems under FDA guidance. Force at 40 mm displacement characterizes post-yield behavior relevant to fatigue life prediction. All three QoIs are explicitly listed in the ASTM F1717 standard and FDA's orthopedic screw guidance document as required reporting metrics."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/relevance-of-validation-activities",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activity replicates the intended COU geometry, loading mode, and material system; any differences between validation scenario and COU are documented and bounded.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity directly replicates the COU: same screw design (non-cannulated 7.5 mm), same loading mode (ASTM F1717 compression-bending), same material system (Ti-6Al-4V), and same assembly configuration (pedicle screw + rod + UHMWPE vertebral body block surrogate). The only difference is the use of standardized surrogate blocks rather than cadaveric bone; this difference is bounded by sensitivity analysis showing < 3% QoI change across the range of surrogate block stiffness values."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/decision/cou1-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/actor/credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "Twelve of thirteen V&V 40 credibility factors meet or exceed their required levels. The single below-threshold factor (Test conditions, achieved 2 vs. required 3) is compensated by strong performance across all quantitative output comparison metrics (E/uval < 1.96 for all three QoIs) and high equivalency between validation and COU scenarios. The overall credibility evidence package is sufficient to support a Medium assurance level conclusion for the non-cannulated pedicle screw compression-bending prediction.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
